---
import BlogPostLayout from '../layouts/BlogPostLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<style>
  .prose ol {list-style: none; padding-left: 0; margin-bottom: 1.25rem;}
  .prose ol li {display: flex; gap: 1rem; margin-bottom: 1.25rem; line-height: 1.75; color: rgb(113 113 122);}
  :global(.dark) .prose ol li {color: rgb(161 161 170);}
  .prose ol li .num {min-width: 2rem; height: 2rem; background: #2563EB; color: white; border-radius: 50%; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; font-weight: 700; font-size: 0.8rem; flex-shrink: 0; margin-top: 2px;}
</style>

<BlogPostLayout
  title="Why Flutter is better?"
  description="8 reasons why Flutter stands out as the best cross-platform framework — from single codebase to native performance and future-proofing."
  canonicalUrl="https://waseemarain4u.github.io/my-portfolio/blog-article-why-flutter"
  ogImage="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1607252650355-f7fd0460ccdb?w=1200&q=80"
  tag="Flutter"
  date="Jun 21, 2023"
  readTime="2 min read"
  mediumUrl="https://medium.com/@waseemarain_98671/why-flutter-is-better-eafb30b89e25"
>
  <p>Flutter, developed by Google, is a popular cross-platform framework known for its numerous advantages over other frameworks. After years of building production apps with Flutter across Android, iOS, Web, and Desktop, here are the reasons why Flutter consistently stands out.</p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      <span class="num">1</span>
      <div><strong class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Single Codebase.</strong> Flutter allows developers to write a single codebase that runs on iOS, Android, Web, and Desktop. You don't need to maintain separate codebases for different platforms — this significantly reduces development time and effort, and keeps your product consistent everywhere.</div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="num">2</span>
      <div><strong class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Fast Development.</strong> Flutter's hot reload lets you see code changes almost instantly without restarting the app. This dramatically speeds up the development loop — you iterate quickly, fix bugs in real-time, and experiment with UI without losing app state.</div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="num">3</span>
      <div><strong class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Native Performance.</strong> Flutter uses the Skia rendering engine (now Impeller) to draw its own UI directly on the GPU. Apps compile to native ARM code and run directly on the device's hardware — the result is excellent performance and responsiveness that rivals truly native apps.</div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="num">4</span>
      <div><strong class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Rich UI.</strong> Flutter ships with a comprehensive set of customizable widgets that follow both Material Design and Cupertino guidelines. You get beautiful, consistent interfaces across platforms without writing platform-specific UI code.</div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="num">5</span>
      <div><strong class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Access to Native Features.</strong> Flutter provides excellent native integration through its plugin system. Camera, geolocation, Bluetooth, biometrics, push notifications — the pub.dev ecosystem covers virtually every device capability you'll need in a production app.</div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="num">6</span>
      <div><strong class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Strong Community and Support.</strong> Flutter has a large, active developer community with thousands of open-source packages, tutorials, and resources. The community grows every year — finding answers, getting support, and discovering solutions is rarely a problem.</div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="num">7</span>
      <div><strong class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Cost-effectiveness.</strong> One codebase means one team. You don't need separate iOS and Android specialists — a Flutter team delivers to all platforms simultaneously. For startups and agencies, the cost savings compound quickly.</div>
    </li>
    <li>
      <span class="num">8</span>
      <div><strong class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 dark:text-white">Future-proofing.</strong> Flutter is backed by Google with consistent investment and a clear roadmap. Regular updates, new platform targets, and a stable long-term vision make it a reliable foundation for any serious app project.</div>
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p>While Flutter has numerous advantages, it's important to consider your specific project requirements and the expertise of your development team before choosing any framework. That said, for most cross-platform projects I encounter, Flutter is the right answer.</p>

  <div slot="more-articles">
    <section class="bg-zinc-50 dark:bg-zinc-900/40 py-16">
      <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6">
        <h2 class="font-display font-bold text-2xl text-zinc-900 dark:text-white mb-8">More articles</h2>
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
          {[
            { href: 'blog-article', img: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1607252650355-f7fd0460ccdb?w=700&q=80', alt: 'Clean Architecture', date: 'May 10, 2025', title: 'Why I switched from MVC to Clean Architecture in Flutter' },
            { href: 'blog-article-bloc', img: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1516321318423-f06f85e504b3?w=700&q=80', alt: 'State management', date: 'Feb 18, 2025', title: 'BLoC, Riverpod, or Provider? My honest take after 4 years' },
            { href: 'blog-article-performance', img: 'https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1461749280684-dccba630e2f6?w=700&q=80', alt: 'Performance', date: 'Dec 2, 2024', title: "5 Flutter performance mistakes I made so you don't have to" },
          ].map(p => (
            <article class="group bg-white dark:bg-zinc-900 rounded-2xl overflow-hidden border border-zinc-100 dark:border-zinc-800 hover:border-accent transition-all hover:-translate-y-1">
              <div class="pf w-full h-40"><img src={p.img} alt={p.alt} loading="lazy"></div>
              <div class="p-5">
                <p class="text-xs text-zinc-400 mb-2">{p.date}</p>
                <a href={`${base}${p.href}`}><h3 class="font-display font-bold text-base text-zinc-900 dark:text-white group-hover:text-accent transition-colors">{p.title}</h3></a>
              </div>
            </article>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</BlogPostLayout>
